(251, 1, '2011-05-08 19:01:36', '2011-05-08 19:01:36', 'I met Josh To in southern Haiti last year through a mutual friend. He was there with BRUTE LABS doing a needs assessment, I was working for an American NGO and we’ve kept in touch since then. I found aid work to be a wonderful way to visit exciting places, and after briefly seeing Cairo during the Egyptian Revolution I was eager to get back to the Middle East. With the prospect of starting a master’s degree only a few months away, I decided to travel to Libya to try to find a relief worker job as I had done with relative ease in Haiti a year ago. The few aid organizations that had arrived in Libya, however, were still weeks away from hiring staff and thus I was relegated to the role of freelance photographer and spent most of my time traveling with a journalist I’d also met in Haiti. Josh asked me to share my experiences and feelings from the trip. There is so much to say, but I’ll keep it to the feelings I remember most vividly, along with a few observations about the developing situation in Libya. I should mention that after a month there, I still have no idea how to spell Qaddafi but I’m going with the New York Times’ version.\r\n\r\nWitnessing the Libyan Civil War provided a surreal contrast of the finest qualities of human beings, and the absolute worst. Warmth, hospitality, and the eternal struggle of man to be free, seen alongside the atrocities committed by Qaddafi forces, many of whom were fighting for money rather than a cause. I saw the horrible, heartbreaking realities of war but I think I’ll remember the time I spent with the rebels more, for their courage, kindness and grace in their country’s darkest hour. Almost immediately after setting foot in Benghazi I was charmed by the generosity of the Libyan people. Many had never seen a Westerner before, and yet treated each of us as a long-lost brother. When our bus into town arrived around 3 AM, a Libyan man we had only just met offered us a place to stay the night. When we awoke the next morning, we found that he had offered us his bedroom while he slept on the couch. After only the briefest of introductions, I was routinely invited to sit in family homes for lunch, coffee, and conversations in the universal language of smiles.\r\nRegarding my thoughts on the war itself, I can only say that I hope it ends quickly, although that does not seem likely at this point. Without a doubt, there is plenty of blame to share for the current stalemate. The rebels thought that after they expelled government troops from Benghazi that Qaddafi would bow to popular and Western pressure like Ali and Mubarak before him. They never considered the possibility that they would have to fight his armored divisions and foreign mercenaries for every inch from Benghazi to Tripoli. For its part, NATO has already implemented the Council’s first and most important request, of setting up a no-fly zone over Libya that has so far prevented any airborne assaults from Qaddafi loyalists. But you give a mouse a cookie and he’s gonna want some air strikes, specifically on Qaddafi’s missile batteries and other heavy artillery. Many Libyans cannot fathom why NATO would sit idly by with its vastly superior weaponry while rebels soldiers fall to Qaddafi’s mortars, missiles, and tanks. The most alarming aspect of the stalemate is that between Qaddafi’s mountain of cash and the rebel-controlled eastern oil fields, both sides have the money to keep the conflict going indefinitely.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nIn the media, the Transitional Council found its greatest advantage over the Qaddafi regime. At the onset of the fighting, Western journalists were offered free 5 night stays at the Hotel Ouzu, Benghazi’s grand hotel, subsidized by the Transitional Council’s petrodollars. Press conferences with Transitional Council spokesmen, military leaders and even the Libyan Boy Scouts are advertised in the Ouzu lobby each day, and the Council’s Media Center is a phone call away for any journalist needing a translator or ride to the front lines. Meanwhile, journalists in Tripoli are herded around the city to staged pro-government events that often include schoolchildren acting like overjoyed Epcot center robots or Qaddafi spasmodically shaking his fists from the sunroof of a limousine, looking more like the corpse-puppet of “Weekend at Bernie’s” than a head of state.\r\nIf you had asked me at the beginning of 2011 whether I would approve of U.S. involvement in a third conflict in the Middle East, I would have said no regardless of the circumstances. After seeing Benghazi, I firmly believe that the U.S. made the right choice. To anyone upset with President Obama for “dragging the country into a war without consulting the American people” please understand this: Qaddafi’s tanks were about 5 miles from the Benghazi city limits when the international coalition destroyed them. The Qaddafi loyalists’ clearly stated goal was the annihilation of the uprising in the de facto rebel capital, a city of over 700,000. There was no time for congressional hearings and I, for one, am glad that there wasn’t a massacre in Benghazi. Nicolas Sarkozy’s comically early recognition of the Transitional Council and commitment of military support that he must have known only the U.S. or NATO could provide smacked of a lonely teenager: in seeking acceptance, offering to drive his friends to the movies before asking his father if he could borrow the car. As much as Sarko’s godlike status in Libya made my American blood boil, even a blind squirrel finds a nut once in a while and he is to be commended for issuing the initial rallying cry. It remains to be seen how long the honeymoon between Libya and the West will last, but at the very least I believe that Libyans will remember that NATO averted a bloodbath in Benghazi.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThe Libyan citizenry has heard all the negative things about America--our lust for oil, our history of meddling in other countries’ affairs—and for the most part they genuinely believe the U.S. and NATO are here to help. One Libyan man said to me “Look, we know America is not a charity, but we think they come to help now. If they want to buy our oil afterwards, so what? What are we going to do with it, drink it?” I sincerely hope NATO continues to take care to handle the situation here thoughtfully. Much has been said about the “rag-tag” rebel army, with Robert Gates referring to the rebellion as not much more than a “pick-up game.” That’s an accurate assessment, but the rebel army is not without its merits. I was awed by the bravery I saw in Libya, and inspired by the unwavering commitment to secular democracy and freedom from tyranny (see: American Revolution). It takes an intense desire for freedom and democracy (not to mention balls of solid brass) to hop into a ’85 Toyota with a Soviet-era machine gun and engage a tank division. The rebels want to liberate Tripoli themselves, without foreign ground troops, and want Qaddafi alive for a trial, not executed. They understand the difficulties inherent in asking for airstrikes from countries who are already weary of Middle Eastern conflicts, and vaguely suspicious of the Middle East in general, but the fact that they’re asking shows they want a positive relationship with the West\r\n\r\nThe rebel cause is unmistakably the right “side of history” to which President Obama refers. The potential gains from being on the right side of Libyan history are enormous; a democratic, capitalistic and wealthy pro-Western Islamic society. The alternative is frightening; another strategically located, oil-rich Middle Eastern country with a heart broken by the West and an open ear to fundamentalist rhetoric. Like I said before, I hope that NATO and the rebels begin to communicate more effectively and bring a swift end to this war, but both parties have their work cut out for them.\r\n\r\nIt’s a difficult choice in a town of such overwhelming hospitality, but my favorite place to be in Benghazi was Karaman, a quaint, smoky Turkish restaurant run by the jolly Artur. Artur speaks Turkish, Arabic and even German from a 15-year stay in Bonn. I can butcher enough German words that we could communicate and since most of my German vocabulary relates to drinking anyways--and Artur pours his 180 proof moonshine liberally for his friends--we quickly developed a glorious, if hazy, friendship. After founding successful restaurants in Turkey, Germany and Holland, he chose to open one in Benghazi because of the massive influx of workers from Turkish companies. On my last night in town I asked him if he intended to stay in Benghazi for long. “No!” he replied emphatically. “The people don’t drink, they cover up their women. They are not right in the head and they won’t change when Qaddafi is gone.” I clinked glasses with Artur based on our mutual appreciation of a stiff drink and an emancipated woman, but I disagree with my friend on his last point. I believe Libyans are just fine in the head and clearly committed to change. They’ve demonstrated as much by sacrificing their very lives for it, and need only to be rid of their ruthless dictator and to find a market for their vast oil reserves (I’m pretty sure someone will be interested) to begin building a progressive, democratic society.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1280"]<a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-Rx0QN4GxkIE/Tccl8oLzTrI/AAAAAAAAAB8/PyGW-NIO8ow/s1600/IMG_6543.jpg"><img title="A man jumps over the wall of a shelled building in Ajdabiya" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-Rx0QN4GxkIE/Tccl8oLzTrI/AAAAAAAAAB8/PyGW-NIO8ow/s1600/IMG_6543.jpg" alt="" width="1280" height="853" /></a> A man jumps over the wall of a shelled building in Ajdabiya[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1280"]<a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-RpPATVbAIA0/Tccl8rNklFI/AAAAAAAAAB0/J8Vfe3CaXYA/s1600/IMG_6515.jpg"><img title="An unexploded shell wedged next to an herb gard