ay for any journalist needing a translator or ride to the front lines. Meanwhile, journalists in Tripoli are herded around the city to staged pro-government events that often include schoolchildren acting like overjoyed Epcot center robots or Qaddafi spasmodically shaking his fists from the sunroof of a limousine, looking more like the corpse-puppet of “Weekend at Bernie’s” than a head of state.\r\nIf you had asked me at the beginning of 2011 whether I would approve of U.S. involvement in a third conflict in the Middle East, I would have said no regardless of the circumstances. After seeing Benghazi, I firmly believe that the U.S. made the right choice. To anyone upset with President Obama for “dragging the country into a war without consulting the American people” please understand this: Qaddafi’s tanks were about 5 miles from the Benghazi city limits when the international coalition destroyed them. The Qaddafi loyalists’ clearly stated goal was the annihilation of the uprising in the de facto rebel capital, a city of over 700,000. There was no time for congressional hearings and I, for one, am glad that there wasn’t a massacre in Benghazi. Nicolas Sarkozy’s comically early recognition of the Transitional Council and commitment of military support that he must have known only the U.S. or NATO could provide smacked of a lonely teenager: in seeking acceptance, offering to drive his friends to the movies before asking his father if he could borrow the car. As much as Sarko’s godlike status in Libya made my American blood boil, even a blind squirrel finds a nut once in a while and he is to be commended for issuing the initial rallying cry. It remains to be seen how long the honeymoon between Libya and the West will last, but at the very least I believe that Libyans will remember that NATO averted a bloodbath in Benghazi.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThe Libyan citizenry has heard all the negative things about America--our lust for oil, our history of meddling in other countries’ affairs—and for the most part they genuinely believe the U.S. and NATO are here to help. One Libyan man said to me “Look, we know America is not a charity, but we think they come to help now. If they want to buy our oil afterwards, so what? What are we going to do with it, drink it?” I sincerely hope NATO continues to take care to handle the situation here thoughtfully. Much has been said about the “rag-tag” rebel army, with Robert Gates referring to the rebellion as not much more than a “pick-up game.” That’s an accurate assessment, but the rebel army is not without its merits. I was awed by the bravery I saw in Libya, and inspired by the unwavering commitment to secular democracy and freedom from tyranny (see: American Revolution). It takes an intense desire for freedom and democracy (not to mention balls of solid brass) to hop into a ’85 Toyota with a Soviet-era machine gun and engage a tank division. The rebels want to liberate Tripoli themselves, without foreign ground troops, and want Qaddafi alive for a trial, not executed. They understand the difficulties inherent in asking for airstrikes from countries who are already weary of Middle Eastern conflicts, and vaguely suspicious of the Middle East in general, but the fact that they’re asking shows they want a positive relationship with the West\r\n\r\nThe rebel cause is unmistakably the right “side of history” to which President Obama refers. The potential gains from being on the right side of Libyan history are enormous; a democratic, capitalistic and wealthy pro-Western Islamic society. The alternative is frightening; another strategically located, oil-rich Middle Eastern country with a heart broken by the West and an open ear to fundamentalist rhetoric. Like I said before, I hope that NATO and the rebels begin to communicate more effectively and bring a swift end to this war, but both parties have their work cut out for them.\r\n\r\nIt’s a difficult choice in a town of such overwhelming hospitality, but my favorite place to be in Benghazi was Karaman, a quaint, smoky Turkish restaurant run by the jolly Artur. Artur speaks Turkish, Arabic and even German from a 15-year stay in Bonn. I can butcher enough German words that we could communicate and since most of my German vocabulary relates to drinking anyways--and Artur pours his 180 proof moonshine liberally for his friends--we quickly developed a glorious, if hazy, friendship. After founding successful restaurants in Turkey, Germany and Holland, he chose to open one in Benghazi because of the massive influx of workers from Turkish companies. On my last night in town I asked him if he intended to stay in Benghazi for long. “No!” he replied emphatically. “The people don’t drink, they cover up their women. They are not right in the head and they won’t change when Qaddafi is gone.” I clinked glasses with Artur based on our mutual appreciation of a stiff drink and an emancipated woman, but I disagree with my friend on his last point. I believe Libyans are just fine in the head and clearly committed to change. They’ve demonstrated as much by sacrificing their very lives for it, and need only to be rid of their ruthless dictator and to find a market for their vast oil reserves (I’m pretty sure someone will be interested) to begin building a progressive, democratic society.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1280"]<a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-Rx0QN4GxkIE/Tccl8oLzTrI/AAAAAAAAAB8/PyGW-NIO8ow/s1600/IMG_6543.jpg"><img title="A man jumps over the wall of a shelled building in Ajdabiya" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-Rx0QN4GxkIE/Tccl8oLzTrI/AAAAAAAAAB8/PyGW-NIO8ow/s1600/IMG_6543.jpg" alt="" width="1280" height="853" /></a> A man jumps over the wall of a shelled building in Ajdabiya[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1280"]<a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-RpPATVbAIA0/Tccl8rNklFI/AAAAAAAAAB0/J8Vfe3CaXYA/s1600/IMG_6515.jpg"><img title="An unexploded shell wedged next to an herb garden in the courtyard of an Ajdabiya home" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-RpPATVbAIA0/Tccl8rNklFI/AAAAAAAAAB0/J8Vfe3CaXYA/s1600/IMG_6515.jpg" alt="" width="1280" height="853" /></a> An unexploded shell wedged next to an herb garden in the courtyard of an Ajdabiya home[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-WQgCdMxHvbo/Tccl8SUJXMI/AAAAAAAAABs/Ka2Vv9f5oSw/s400/IMG_6375.jpg"><img class="alignnone" title="Friday prayers in Benghazi, Qaddafi banned public gatherings so this is the first time in four decades Libyans have been able to freely express themselves" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-WQgCdMxHvbo/Tccl8SUJXMI/AAAAAAAAABs/Ka2Vv9f5oSw/s400/IMG_6375.jpg" alt="" width="267" height="400" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="400"]<a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-k-Jsf96dUU8/Tccl8LWNCsI/AAAAAAAAABk/s35glDntF4M/s400/IMG_6359.jpg"><img title="“No Al Qaeda, No Hezbollah” sign at Friday prayers in Benghazi" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-k-Jsf96dUU8/Tccl8LWNCsI/AAAAAAAAABk/s35glDntF4M/s400/IMG_6359.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="267" /></a> “No Al Qaeda, No Hezbollah” sign at Friday prayers in Benghazi[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="400"]<a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-fR_qOMXidSg/Tccl72VgWLI/AAAAAAAAABc/zyoYisI9UE8/s400/IMG_6358.jpg"><img title="A Libyan man waves an American flag at Friday prayers in Benghazi" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-fR_qOMXidSg/Tccl72VgWLI/AAAAAAAAABc/zyoYisI9UE8/s400/IMG_6358.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="267" /></a> A Libyan man waves an American flag at Friday prayers in Benghazi[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="400"]<a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-7by4CbW1q8g/TccloApKXjI/AAAAAAAAABM/MF2YLRflzo8/s400/IMG_6223.jpg"><img title="A pickup truck fashioned into a convertible to accommodate a rocket battery" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-7by4CbW1q8g/TccloApKXjI/AAAAAAAAABM/MF2YLRflzo8/s400/IMG_6223.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="267" /></a> A pickup truck fashioned into a convertible to accommodate a rocket battery[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1280"]<a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-Pm6zxMRM3JQ/TcclnyM7ffI/AAAAAAAAABE/MPCbmiPctYs/s1600/IMG_6150.jpg"><img class=" " title="A rebel soldier throws up a peace sign while manning an anti-aircraft gun near the front lines" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-Pm6zxMRM3JQ/TcclnyM7ffI/AAAAAAAAABE/MPCbmiPctYs/s1600/IMG_6150.jpg" alt="" width="1280" height="853" /></a> A rebel soldier throws up a peace sign while manning an anti-aircraft gun near the front lines[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="400"]<a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-O7DpUjBGrWY/TcclnZELCFI/AAAAAAAAAA8/9awtLPpoPrU/s1600/IMG_6125.jpg"><img title="Remnants of a tank destroyed by NATO on the outskirts of Benghazi" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-O7DpUjBGrWY/TcclnZELCFI/AAAAAAAAAA8/9awtLPpoPrU/s400/IMG_6125.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="267" /></a> Remnants of a tank destroyed by NATO on the outskirts of Benghazi[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="400"]<a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-pRya8vAjh28/TcclnKSKtsI/AAAAAAAAAA0/NdEEkrqEdCk/s400/IMG_6088.jpg"><img title="A 15 year old rebel, injured in the initial uprising in Benghazi, waits for his leg to heal." src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-pRya8vAjh28/TcclnKSKtsI/AAAAAAAAAA0/NdEEkrqEdCk/s400/IMG_6088.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="267" /></a> A 15 year old rebel, injured in the initial uprising in Benghazi, waits for his leg to heal.[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'A BRUTE friend in Lybia', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '251-revision-2', '', '', '2012-10-31 19:01:36', '2012-10-31 19:01:36', '', 251, 'http://localhost:8888/2012/10/251-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(254, 1, '2011-05-03 19:03:36', '2011-05-03 19:03:36', '<a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-DJPs0cBwaic/TcDLOPl4fOI/AAAAAAAAAAs/byWzCTqdIdc/s1600/SappiRUN.JPG"><img class="alignnone" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-DJPs0cBwaic/TcDLOPl4fOI/AAAAAAAAAAs/byWzCTqdIdc/s1600/SappiRUN.JPG" alt="" width="1296" height="968" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBRUTE LABS has worked with Sappi’s <a href="http://www.na.sappi.com/ideasthatmatterNA/index.html">Ideas That Matter</a> grant program for a few years now. Their generous funding has helped us to address childhood obesity in 15 low income bay area elementary schools with the <a href="http://www.brutelabs.org/run/">RUN!</a> project, as well as address the pervasive plight of homeless in San Francisco through <a href="http://www.brutelabs.org/projectopen.html">projectOPEN</a>.\r\nWe were honored to be included in this year’s call for entries book, with one of my all-time favorite images in the annuls of BRUTE LABS: a picture of the RUN! winners at Cesar Chavez Elementary School in East Palo Alto, CA where we piloted the project before expanding throughout the bay area.\r\nIf you or someone you know have a project that can help your community or the world, head over to Sappi’s <a href="http://www.na.sappi.com/ideasthatmatter/callforentry">call for entries page</a> and submit your idea today! The deadline is July 15,2011.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'RUN! Featured in the Sappi "Ideas That Matter" Call for Entries', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'run-featured-in-the-sappi-ideas-that-matter-call-for-entries', '', '', '2012-10-31 19:15:46', '2012-10-31 19:15:46', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/?p=254', 0, 'post', '', 0),
