(257, 1, '2011-03-31 19:06:16', '2011-03-31 19:06:16', '<div>For BRUTE LABS, everything starts with design. Utilizing design, we’ve helped:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Homeless people in Santa Monica gain greater access to resources and learn about the laws that pertain to them (project OPEN)</li>\r\n	<li>Children in low income schools improve their mile-running times by 242% (RUN)</li>\r\n	<li>Communities in Ghana get access to clean drinking water (WellDone)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nEach of those projects showed us the magic of design and how it can be used as a framework to change lives. In the spirit of Opening Day, Chris, our guest blogger for the week, shares an an account of how the “magic” of design touched his own life.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<div><strong>So Much to (G)Love: An Account of How A Design Changed My Life</strong></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div><a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-zc1wfkyP-uY/TZTRbnmiuaI/AAAAAAAAAAM/JdytjypXKNg/s320/glove.jpeg"><img class="alignnone" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-zc1wfkyP-uY/TZTRbnmiuaI/AAAAAAAAAAM/JdytjypXKNg/s320/glove.jpeg" alt="" width="320" height="256" /></a></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>Let’s go ahead and take a good hard look at the picture above. Take it all in….there you go, deep breath…take your time. Now, let''s pause here. What are we looking at?</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>\r\n<em>The Brewers logo ranks with the most utilitarian and unimaginative of signage-- the simplest of logos merely intended to indicate the profession its bearers practiced. The glove and ball is like a visual onomatopoeia, redundant to the point of lunacy; the equivalent of anointing a topographic map of a country to be its flag. Milwaukee brass replaced the revered and wholly contextually appropriate </em><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_74UZ5-xABqc/SGElWYEe49I/AAAAAAAAAJk/dK9T_aowL6I/s1600-h/Brewers1970logo.gif"><em>Beer Barrel Man</em></a></span><em> for this? Just change the team''s name to the Milwaukee Baseball Players to match that dumb logo, you idiots.</em><sup><em><a name="sdfootnote2anc" href="http://www.blogger.com/post-create.g?blogID=8361741419744270858#sdfootnote2sym"></a><sup>2</sup></em></sup>\r\n\r\nBut, then it happened. I half-blew my own mind after parsing out a disguised "w" and "9" from looking at the logo upside down. But, after flipping the image right side up and catching sight of that glorious "M" and "b” for the first time, my transformation was complete. I was speechless…maybe even breathless…the improbable had materialized right before my eyes. That proud logo, from that rich land of sausage noshing and cheese mongering, turned my world upside down…or should I say, right side up?</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>\r\nYou probably never forget that first time you realized that something seemingly inanimate or unintelligent had outwitted you…"you feel as Victor Frankenstein must have when the dead conglomeration of sewn together spare parts suddenly opened its watery eyes. Oh my God, it''s breathing, you realize. Maybe it''s even thinking"<sup><a name="sdfootnote3anc" href="http://www.blogger.com/post-create.g?blogID=8361741419744270858#sdfootnote3sym"></a><sup>3</sup></sup>. The Brewers'' logo was that for me; it was <em>The Sixth Sense</em>, it was <em>Se7en</em>, it was <em>The Usual Suspects</em>, just in blue and yellow dye. The Glove and Ball that I hated was also an "M" and "b" all along? How? WHAAA!!??? <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TO5wryDdEI0">Clever girl.</a></span></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>\r\nI was changed. I began to wonder that if a logo could be both a picture and letters, then what wasn''t possible?</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div><a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-ce2b7ioDxNU/TZTR6nS2pVI/AAAAAAAAAAU/NwPguXDAW3Q/s320/Rollie-Fingers.jpg"><img class="alignnone" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-ce2b7ioDxNU/TZTR6nS2pVI/AAAAAAAAAAU/NwPguXDAW3Q/s320/Rollie-Fingers.jpg" alt="" width="226" height="320" /></a></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>The Best? <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://store.nike.com/us/en_us/?l=shop,pdp,ctr-inline/cid-1/pid-357674&amp;cp=usns_0328071544#l=shop,pdp,ctr-inline/cid-1/pid-357656">This too...</a></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>\r\nFamed illusionist and madman, David Blaine, keenly states, "When people witness magic, they never forget if for the rest of their lives…Magic strips away logic, it confronts fears, and brings us to a place of constant wonder and enchantment."</div>\r\n<div>\r\nGlove and Ball has transformed scores of people who have come across it, some of whom can be found in Facebook groups like ''Best Day of My Life: When I Realized the Old Brewers Logo is an M and a B'' and ''When I realized that the brewer''s glove logo was an M and B it blew my mind'' ( who''s description is: "Never was quite the same afterwards…").</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>\r\nLike them, I won''t forget when I witnessed the magic and depth of the Brewers logo for the first time; my mind''s heart grew three sizes that day. Because on that day, I was encouraged to confront the idea that the world wasn''t as rigidly organized as I previously thought and was introduced to the possibility of possibilities. I am still enchanted...</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>\r\nThe logo encouraged me to believe in magic, but not the kind of magic learned at Hogwarts or reserved for live action fantasy role playing. More like the kind of magic that compelled someone to conceive the first ever telescope, or play the first ever power chord, or bake the first ever chocolate cake (or invent the first ever "magic" trick). Glove and Ball is an artifact of the creativity and resourcefulness of the human spirit that can blur the lines between what isn''t there and what can be…between what’s improbable and what’s inevitable. It''s an artifact of the kind of magic that men and women create.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="218"]<a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-ljVMHttk7g8/TZTSIaDOeCI/AAAAAAAAAAc/L863rKjQKww/s1600/glovesmallwhite.jpg"><img src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-ljVMHttk7g8/TZTSIaDOeCI/AAAAAAAAAAc/L863rKjQKww/s320/glovesmallwhite.jpg" alt="" width="218" height="231" /></a> One Logo to Rule Them All/Hail the Brewers Glove and Ball![/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you’re interested in getting another hidden logo fix in, check out:<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://www.graphicdesignblog.org/hidden-logos-in-graphic-designing/"> http://www.graphicdesignblog.org/hidden-logos-in-graphic-designing/</a></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<div>Sources:</div>\r\n<div>Blaine, David. <span style="text-decoration: underline;">Mysterious Stranger: A Book of Magic</span>. New York: Villard Books, 2003.</div>\r\n<div>King, Stephen. <span style="text-decoration: underline;">On Writing: A Memoir of the Craft</span>. New York: Pocket Books, 2000.</div>\r\n<div><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milwaukee_Brewers">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milwaukee_Brewers</a></span></div>\r\n<div><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://sullybaseball.blogspot.com/2009/02/sully-baseball-honors-bad-ass-glove-and.html">http://sullybaseball.blogspot.com/2009/02/sully-baseball-honors-bad-ass-glove-and.html</a></span></div>\r\n<div><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://community.sportsbubbler.com/blogs/the_daily_drink/archive/2009/08/28/old-school-why-we-still-love-the-logo.aspx">http://community.sportsbubbler.com/blogs/the_daily_drink/archive/2009/08/28/old-school-why-we-still-love-the-logo.aspx</a></span></div>\r\n<div align="CENTER"><em>\r\n</em></div>\r\n<div><a name="sdfootnote1sym" href="http://www.blogger.com/post-create.g?blogID=8361741419744270858#sdfootnote1anc"></a>1 *SPOILER: Oh, what sweet sense it makes. The "M" is found in the three right fingers of the mitt''s webbing, on the upper right; the "b" is the rest of it. The M and b, of course, are the Milwaukee Brewers'' initials.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div id="sdfootnote2">\r\n<div><a name="sdfootnote2sym" href="http://www.blogger.com/post-create.g?blogID=8361741419744270858#sdfootnote2anc"></a>2 After some reflection, I probably would be fine with the logo even if there wasn''t a secondary meaning to it. There''s a simplicity here: a no frills symbol for a hard-nosed city and a classic game. It''s open palm/glove is welcoming: the hand looks as if it might be waving or inviting you for a High Five. It''s also engaging in that it captures an extremely visceral moment -- a snapshot at or right before a moment of impact--the loud THWAPP! of a ball slapping leather. One could also see a coy and slick haired Cloud Guy from Mario Brothers half-hiding behind the "b".</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<a name="sdfootnote3sym" href="http://www.blogger.com/post-create.g?blogID=8361741419744270858#sdfootnote3anc"></a>3 Stephen King actually used those words to describe the sensation one has after crafting one''s first really good paragraph, in his superb <em>On Writing</em>. I loved this description so much, I kinda just wanted an excuse to use it somewhere.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n</div>', 'So Much to (G)Love', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'so-much-to-glove', '', '', '2012-10-31 19:06:39', '2012-10-31 19:06:39', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/?p=257', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(258, 1, '2012-10-31 19:06:01', '2012-10-31 19:06:01', '<div>For BRUTE LABS, everything starts with design. Utilizing design, we’ve helped:\n<ul>\n	<li>Homeless people in Santa Monica gain greater access to resources and learn about the laws that pertain to them (project OPEN)</li>\n	<li>Children in low income schools improve their mile-running times by 242% (RUN)</li>\n	<li>Communities in Ghana get access to clean drinking water (WellDone)</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n&nbsp;\n\nEach of those projects showed us the magic of design and how it can be used as a framework to change lives. In the spirit of Opening Day, Chris, our guest blogger for the week, shares an an account of how the “magic” of design touched his own life.\n\n&nbsp;\n<div><strong>So Much to (G)Love: An Account of How A Design Changed My Life</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n<div><a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-zc1wfkyP-uY/TZTRbnmiuaI/AAAAAAAAAAM/JdytjypXKNg/s320/glove.jpeg"><img class="alignnone" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-zc1wfkyP-uY/TZTRbnmiuaI/AAAAAAAAAAM/JdytjypXKNg/s320/glove.jpeg" alt="" width="320" height="256" /></a></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>Let’s go ahead and take a good hard look at the picture above. Take it all in….there you go, deep breath…take your time. Now, let''s pause here. What are we looking at?</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\n<em>The Brewers logo ranks with the most utilitarian and unimaginative of signage-- the simplest of logos merely intended to indicate the profession its bearers practiced. The glove and ball is like a visual onomatopoeia, redundant to the point of lunacy; the equivalent of anointing a topographic map of a country to be its flag. Milwaukee brass replaced the revered and wholly contextually appropriate </em><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_74UZ5-xABqc/SGElWYEe49I/AAAAAAAAAJk/dK9T_aowL6I/s1600-h/Brewers1970logo.gif"><em>Beer Barrel Man</em></a></span><em> for this? Just change the team''s name to the Milwaukee Baseball Players to match that dumb logo, you idiots.</em><sup><em><a name="sdfootnote2anc" href="http://www.blogger.com/post-create.g?blogID=8361741419744270858#sdfootnote2sym"></a><sup>2</sup></em></sup>\n\nBut, then it happened. I half-blew my own mind after parsing out a disguised "w" and "9" from looking at the logo upside down. But, after flipping the image right side up and catching sight of that glorious "M" and "b” for the first time, my transformation was complete. I was speechless…maybe even breathless…the improbable had materialized right before my eyes. That proud logo, from that rich land of sausage noshing and cheese mongering, turned my world upside down…or should I say, right side up?</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\nYou probably never forget that first time you realized that something seemingly inanimate or unintelligent had outwitted you…"you feel as Victor Frankenstein must have when the dead conglomeration of sewn together spare parts suddenly opened its watery eyes. Oh my God, it''s breathing, you realize. Maybe it''s even thinking"<sup><a name="sdfootnote3anc" href="http://www.blogger.com/post-create.g?blogID=8361741419744270858#sdfootnote3sym"></a><sup>3</sup></sup>. The Brewers'' logo was that for me; it was <em>The Sixth Sense</em>, it was <em>Se7en</em>, it was <em>The Usual Suspects</em>, just in blue and yellow dye. The Glove and Ball that I hated was also an "M" and "b" all along? How? WHAAA!!??? <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TO5wryDdEI0">Clever girl.</a></span></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\nI was changed. I began to wonder that if a logo could be both a picture and letters, then what wasn''t possible?</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-ce2b7ioDxNU/TZTR6nS2pVI/AAAAAAAAAAU/NwPguXDAW3Q/s320/Rollie-Fingers.jpg"><img class="alignnone" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-ce2b7ioDxNU/TZTR6nS2pVI/AAAAAAAAAAU/NwPguXDAW3Q/s320/Rollie-Fingers.jpg" alt="" width="226" height="320" /></a></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\n<div>The Best? <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://store.nike.com/us/en_us/?l=shop,pdp,ctr-inline/cid-1/pid-357674&amp;cp=usns_0328071544#l=shop,pdp,ctr-inline/cid-1/pid-357656">This too...</a></span></div>\n</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\nFamed illusionist and madman, David Blaine, keenly states, "When people witness magic, they never forget if for the rest of their lives…Magic strips away logic, it confronts fears, and brings us to a place of constant wonder and enchantment."</div>\n<div>\nGlove and Ball has transformed scores of people who have come across it, some of whom can be found in Facebook groups like ''Best Day of My Life: When I Realized the Old Brewers Logo is an M and a B'' and ''When I realized that the brewer''s glove logo was an M and B it blew my mind'' ( who''s description is: "Never was quite the same afterwards…").</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\nLike them, I won''t forget when I witnessed the magic and depth of the Brewers logo for the first time; my mind''s heart grew three sizes that day. Because on that day, I was encouraged to confront the idea that the world wasn''t as rigidly organized as I previously thought and was introduced to the possibility of possibilities. I am still enchanted...</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\nThe logo encouraged me to believe in magic, but not the kind of magic learned at Hogwarts or reserved for live action fantasy role playing. More like the kind of magic that compelled someone to conceive the first ever telescope, or play the first ever power chord, or bake the first ever chocolate cake (or invent the first ever "magic" trick). Glove and Ball is an artifact of the creativity and resourcefulness of the human spirit that can blur the lines between what isn''t there and what can be…between what’s improbable and what’s inevitable. It''s an artifact of the kind of magic that men and women create.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\n\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="218"]<a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-ljVMHttk7g8/TZTSIaDOeCI/AAAAAAAAAAc/L863rKjQKww/s1600/glovesmallwhite.jpg"><img src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-ljVMHttk7g8/TZTSIaDOeCI/AAAAAAAAAAc/L863rKjQKww/s320/glovesmallwhite.jpg" alt="" width="218" height="231" /></a> One Logo to Rule Them All/Hail the Brewers Glove and Ball![/caption]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nIf you’re interested in getting another hidden logo fix in, check out:<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://www.graphicdesignblog.org/hidden-logos-in-graphic-designing/"> http://www.graphicdesignblog.org/hidden-logos-in-graphic-designing/</a></span>\n<div>Sources:</div>\n<div>Blaine, David. <span style="text-decoration: underline;">Mysterious Stranger: A Book of Magic</span>. New York: Villard Books, 2003.</div>\n<div>King, Stephen. <span style="text-decoration: underline;">On Writing: A Memoir of the Craft</span>. New York: Pocket Books, 2000.</div>\n<div><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milwaukee_Brewers">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milwaukee_Brewers</a></span></div>\n<div><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://sullybaseball.blogspot.com/2009/02/sully-baseball-honors-bad-ass-glove-and.html">http://sullybaseball.blogspot.com/2009/02/sully-baseball-honors-bad-ass-glove-and.html</a></span></div>\n<div><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://community.sportsbubbler.com/blogs/the_daily_drink/archive/2009/08/28/old-school-why-we-still-love-the-logo.aspx">http://community.sportsbubbler.com/blogs/the_daily_drink/archive/2009/08/28/old-school-why-we-still-love-the-logo.aspx</a></span></div>\n<div align="CENTER"><em>\n</em></div>\n<div><a name="sdfootnote1sym" href="http://www.blogger.com/post-create.g?blogID=8361741419744270858#sdfootnote1anc"></a>1 *SPOILER: Oh, what sweet sense it makes. The "M" is found in the three right fingers of the mitt''s webbing, on the upper right; the "b" is the rest of it. The M and b, of course, are the Milwaukee Brewers'' initials.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div id="sdfootnote2">\n<div><a name="sdfootnote2sym" href="http://www.blogger.com/post-create.g?blogID=8361741419744270858#sdfootnote2anc"></a>2 After some reflection, I probably would be fine with the logo even if there wasn''t a secondary meaning to it. There''s a simplicity here: a no frills symbol for a hard-nosed city and a classic game. It''s open palm/glove is welcoming: the hand looks as if it might be waving or inviting you for a High Five. It''s also engaging in that it captures an extremely visceral moment -- a snapshot at or right before a moment of impact--the loud THWAPP! of a ball slapping leather. One could also see a coy and slick haired Cloud Guy from Mario Brothers half-hiding behind the "b".</div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n</div>\n<a name="sdfootnote3sym" href="http://www.blogger.com/post-create.g?blogID=8361741419744270858#sdfootnote3anc"></a>3 Stephen King actually used those words to describe the sensation one has after crafting one''s first really good paragraph, in his superb <em>On Writing</em>. I loved this description so much, I kinda just wanted an excuse to use it somewhere.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n</div>', 'So Much to (G)Love', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '257-revision', '', '', '2012-10-31 19:06:01', '2012-10-31 19:06:01', '', 257, 'http://localhost:8888/2012/10/257-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
