(263, 1, '2011-02-01 19:11:30', '2011-02-01 19:11:30', '<div>In December, Joshua To and I (representing <a href="http://www.google.com/url?q=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.soup.is&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNFrTfsjtM24U0LHlbKKpXtuJJiQZg">Soup</a>) and Archie Lee Coates and Jeff Franklin of <a href="http://www.google.com/url?q=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.playlab.org&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNGoxMM7snGocZa3YOQVHk3tWZwo3w">PlayLab</a> traveled to the Red Sea town of Thuwal, Saudi Arabia.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>Out-of-the-Box-Mission: to teach four idea-generation workshops to students ranging from 14-50 years of age at<a href="http://www.google.com/url?q=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.kaust.edu.sa%2F&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNHSX_2dS3tfKdfu-fGhwNGT-8Iwsg">King Abdullah University of Science and Technology (KAUST)</a>. With our four-person team and two KAUST students (Eric Martin and Ernesto Sandoval), we devised and developed solutions with 50 students.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>Our team used these workshops to teach students how to use rapid prototyping and community engagement. It was an eclectic mix of mystery and (according to our title) fresh air: students built pasta towers ensconced by marshmallows, the MA and PhD students generated words onto Post-it notes, and all made fantastic reality-based concepts come alive. We saw local Saudi students partner with Chinese, Mexican and American students as they all came together to problem solve, and in the end, learn about each others’ cultures. These workshops helped students dive into reality-based development problems (environment, population and technology) that are impacting our world. A snapshot of the final projects from the 100 ideas generated include:</div>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li value="1">Hajj Traffic Engineering: A major experiential design effort to restructure the flow of traffic around the <a href="http://www.google.com/url?q=http%3A%2F%2Fislam.about.com%2Fod%2Fmecca%2Fp%2Fkaaba.htm&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNHtY954m7gbiNHqYmPNcJxLxP8CZA">Ka''aba</a> during Hajj (the annual Muslim <a href="http://www.google.com/url?q=http%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FPilgrimage&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNEGeDKXcyXQxKFo_4uAiUOquVfXkw">pilgrimage</a> to <a href="http://www.google.com/url?q=http%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FMecca&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNEUtAFdfS7R2E_Mlz1qD7h90-F-vw">Mecca</a>, <a href="http://www.google.com/url?q=http%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FSaudi_Arabia&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNHsUQDBqdllRhC-Yrcb9mptbQ_ZvQ">Saudi Arabia</a>) and to cut down on the amount of frustrations, injuries, and deaths at the holy site.</li>\r\n	<li>A/C Flower Box: Using the condensation that drops out of air conditioners to water plants.</li>\r\n	<li>Investment Fungi Jeans: a product that gives a user the ability to grow their own clothes, using the natural effects of specific fungi and algae.</li>\r\n	<li>Quake Wave Friend: a series of probes that would collect energy put off through vibrations of natural occurrences and disasters, as a way to capture un-harnessed energy of movement.</li>\r\n	<li>iDream: a device or application that allows people to know or remember what they have dreamt by recording this through a neurological headset.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>The exercises pushed students to invent and configure new approaches to problem solving, all while using their background in science and for some, the humanities. I found Saudi Arabia to be an open playground to explore new ideas and venture into other exciting encounters:</div>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li value="1">The team attended the first Middle East TEDxArabia Talk where <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o2JRLa3cQ6Y">Josh To</a> and <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=USGjpxpcDvo">Archie Lee Coates</a> presented to a Saudi crowd of 1,000. Audience members went wild with the possibility of actually developing a prototype of the projects.</li>\r\n	<li>I worked with 40 inspiring secondary-school female students to encourage them to pitch their ideas and share these inventions with a larger audience.</li>\r\n	<li>We ate the Saudi Arabian national dish of <a href="http://www.google.com/url?q=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.food.com%2Frecipe%2Fal-kabsa-traditional-saudi-rice-chicken-dish-289878&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNFYmwLf3MHlTl8oNElIquismEJbng">Kebsa</a> (lamb on rice) in a public park filled with families until 3 a.m.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>Here''s to more opportunities to build, play, and learn both in the Arabian Peninsula and around the globe.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div><a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_xydTRd18G4Y/TUi0kX_e7oI/AAAAAAAAAD8/v4nnCPyFe6k/s1600/image2.png"><img class="alignnone" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_xydTRd18G4Y/TUi0kX_e7oI/AAAAAAAAAD8/v4nnCPyFe6k/s1600/image2.png" alt="" width="500" height="345" /></a></div>\r\n<div></div>', '“Fresh Air and the Weight of Things”: Finding an Oasis of Ideas in the Saudi Arabian Desert', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'fresh-air-and-the-weight-of-things-finding-an-oasis-of-ideas-in-the-saudi-arabian-desert', '', '', '2012-10-31 19:11:53', '2012-10-31 19:11:53', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/?p=263', 0, 'post', '', 0),
