(268, 1, '2012-10-31 19:09:50', '2012-10-31 19:09:50', 'Back in December, I shared a <a href="http://blog.brutelabs.org/2010/12/has-america-forgotten-about-detroit.html">post</a> detailing how a trip to New Orleans inspired me to learn more about some of the revitalization work being done in Detroit. So Danny Bowman, Joshua Knox and I packed up our winter gear and headed off to Motor City, USA. The intent was to network with folks on the forefront of the revitalization efforts, drop by a museum or two, take in some of the local eateries and attend the <a href="http://www.naias.com/">North American International Auto Show</a>!\r\n“What brought you to Detroit in January?” each person we visited with asked after learning that we hailed from the sunny skies of California.\r\nAdmittedly, we didn’t have a good answer. I guess January seemed as ripe a time to us as any to learn something new. And learn something new, we did.\r\n\r\nThe focus of the trip was broad. In the span of about 4 days, we wanted to learn about the past, present and future of our destination. The landmarks, the museums and the neighborhoods yelled out their stories to us. Yet, these stories wouldn’t have crystallized without the input from some of the amazing leaders that we had a chance to sit down with and learn from.\r\nWe got a glimpse into Veronika’s efforts to combat the difficulties faced by the 32k homeless living on the streets of Detroit during the Winter season. While taking a walk down memory lane, Tom and Peggy Brennan showed us how an old Model T showroom is playing host to the builders of a more sustainable and entrepreneurial future for the city. Two seasoned business leaders, Brian Balasia and Ken Agacinski, shared with us their journey towards economic revitalization, and Karla Henderson at City Hall explained how demolition and community engagement marks the beginning of the rebuilding process. Lisa Richter even gave us a chance to taste delicious lettuce defiantly growing in the harsh winter weather.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="500"]<a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-eKX1hEEC60E/TWMKhTbcpPI/AAAAAAAAAEI/hAXKhOFlesw/s1600/DetroitPost1.jpg"><img title="Hanging with Lisa Richter from Earthworks Urban Farm" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-eKX1hEEC60E/TWMKhTbcpPI/AAAAAAAAAEI/hAXKhOFlesw/s1600/DetroitPost1.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="375" /></a> Hanging with Lisa Richter from Earthworks Urban Farm[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNo one person was more influential to the orchestration of our trip than Phillip Cooley, a local developer and <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/11/17/huffposts-greatest-person_4_n_784906.html">nationally-recognized</a> leader in Detroit’s urban revitalization movement. Phillip is in every sense of the word a true community organizer that extended his hand to a group of strangers and served as an ambassador for his hometown. For that, we are extremely thankful.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="500"]<a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-3x4xrradS8E/TWMKhquiCEI/AAAAAAAAAEM/n01XEqB25MM/s1600/DetroitPost2.jpg"><img title="Epic Pizza Party with Phil Cooley and Friends" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-3x4xrradS8E/TWMKhquiCEI/AAAAAAAAAEM/n01XEqB25MM/s1600/DetroitPost2.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="375" /></a> Epic Pizza Party with Phil Cooley and Friends[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere is no shortage of bad things that one could point out about Detroit in this post. Shuttered windows tug at you and force you to try reconciling where the city is now with the glory days of the past. You can’t help but to think to yourself: How could this happen? This was the Paris of the West, after all.\r\nThese realities scream at you from nearly all directions. Despite these truths, the most lasting impressions from our Midwestern expedition aren’t centered around disrepair and disbelief. Instead, we left feeling inspired and with a richer understanding of the city. We couldn’t help but to take account of how the most lasting memories from the trip focus on the amazing people that we met. In many respects, the adversity that the city has faced has afforded a unique amount of opportunity to the people of Detroit to be entrepreneurial or innovative in their approach to solving problems. The folks that we met are truly and fully committed to the rebuilding of a better cultural, political and economic future for Detroiters.\r\nOne-sided media reports and irregularly attended sociology classes colored some of the ignorance apparent in my previous <a href="http://blog.brutelabs.org/2010/12/has-america-forgotten-about-detroit.html">post</a>. But our experience in Detroit enlightened us and positioned us to speak more responsibly about the collapse and rebirth of Detroit. From a city that we knew nothing of, to a city that we love. Thank you for welcoming us with open arms Detroit! Check out a few pics from our trip <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/brutelabs/">here</a>.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="768"]<a href="http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5300/5411284971_4bc7a85418_b.jpg"><img title="The Brute in BRUTE LABS" src="http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5300/5411284971_4bc7a85418_b.jpg" alt="" width="768" height="1024" /></a> The Brute in BRUTE LABS[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSpecial thanks to the following people:\r\nPhillip Cooley, <a href="http://www.oconnordetroit.com/development/index.htm">O’Connor Realty / Slows BBQ Restaurant</a>\r\nVeronika Scott, <a href="http://detroitempowermentplan.blogspot.com/">The Empowerment Plan</a>\r\nTom and Peggy Brennan, <a href="http://www.greengaragedetroit.com/index.php?title=Main_Page">The Green Garage</a>\r\nBrian Balasia, <a href="http://www.thedigeratiprocess.com/corporate_profile/team.html">Digerati</a>\r\nKen Agacinski, <a href="http://www.themoreprogram.com/">The MORE Program</a>\r\nKarla Henderson, <a href="http://detroitworksproject.com/">Office of Mayor Dave Bing / The Detroit Works Project</a>\r\nLisa Richter, <a href="http://www.cskdetroit.org/EWG/farm.cfm">Earthworks Urban Farm </a>\r\n<strong>If you know of other folks hard at work at revitalizing Detroit, would like to share feedback on this post or have thoughts about where we should visit next, shoot a message to <a href="mailto:dontae@brutelabs.org">dontae@brutelabs.org</a>. I look forward to hearing from you!</strong>', 'BRUTE LABS in Motor City', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '260-revision-3', '', '', '2012-10-31 19:09:50', '2012-10-31 19:09:50', '', 260, 'http://localhost:8888/2012/10/260-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
