(287, 1, '2012-10-31 20:05:41', '2012-10-31 20:05:41', '<div>In what was one of the most memorable BRUTE LABS meetings for me, serendipity brought Shubhranshu Choudhary as a guest speaker. His story about working 20 years with the BBC in southeast Asia and moving on to develop CGNet with MIT captivated our group with it''s BRUTE spirit.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>Since not everyone is able to attend our meetings (but all are welcome!), we asked Shu to be a guest blogger for this week so we could share the captivating experience with everyone.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4007/4367278761_360e01250b_b.jpg"><img title="Figure 1: Citizen journalist" src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4007/4367278761_360e01250b_b.jpg" alt="" width="1024" height="685" /></a> Figure 1: Citizen journalist[/caption]\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div><strong>Background</strong></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>Many of the estimated 80 million members of India’s tribal communities lack access to any mainstream media outlets. This often poses serious barriers to their socio-economic development, as their grievances about government neglect and economic exploitation remain unvoiced. In addition, certain factions (such as the Maoist insurgency) can exploit their frustration and isolation to violent ends.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nTo address this important problem, we have built and deployed CGNet Swara (Voice of Chhattisgarh): a voice portal that enables ordinary citizens to report news and issues of interest. To use it, they call a phone number using any mobile (or fixed line) phone. Callers are prompted to records a story on CGNet Swara. press “1” to record a new message, and “2” to listen to messages that have already been recorded. Once a message has been recorded from the field, professional, trained journalists, who access the system using a Web-based interface, review and verify the report. Approved reports are then made available for playback over the phone. The reports also can be accessed on the CGNet Swara website.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>We deployed CGNet Swara in February 2010 in Chhattisgarh, a tribal region in central India. Since that time, the system has logged more than 10,000 phone calls and 400 approved news stories on our channel. The system has also had anecdotal impact; for example, one citizen report documented that the government had failed to pay teachers for more than six months. Within 10 days of this story going live on our system, the teachers received their payment.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nCGNet Swara empowers marginalized people – including India’s 80 million tribals – by giving them an outlet to communicate with each other and the national and global media. Because the system gives rural, low-literate communities a way to connect using their own words and voices, CGnet Swara also can play an important role in preserving some of India’s ancient tribal languages. Our vision is to scale the service within India and eventually beyond, creating a vibrant ecosystem of citizen news reports that is universally accessible via low-cost mobile phones. While there is already abundant enthusiasm among grassroots users, as a small organization we are seeking institutional support to help scale our system and make this vision a reality.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>CGNet Swara is led by Shubhranshu Choudhary as part of his fellowship with the International Center for Journalists. Technical support was provided by the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and other volunteers.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>CGNet Swara has earned international recognition as the recipient of an mBillionth South Asia Award, as well as the India eGov 2.0 award. It has been profiled by major news outlets such as the BBC, The Hindu, NDTV, and many other publications in India.</div>', 'CGNet Swara: A Voice Portal for Citizen News Journalism in India', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '283-revision-4', '', '', '2012-10-31 20:05:41', '2012-10-31 20:05:41', '', 283, 'http://localhost:8888/2012/10/283-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(288, 1, '2010-11-19 20:07:30', '2010-11-19 20:07:30', 'Gabe Francis, a friend of BRUTE LABS, was a guest blogger just before he embarked on his Kiva fellowship in Costa Rica. Below he shares his reflections of his work as he prepared to return to the concrete jungle in New York he calls home.\r\n-\r\nWhen asked what they think of Costa Rica most people usually refer to the poster in their local travel agency, white palm beaches, virgin cloud forests, and toucans. Yet, there is a side of Costa Rica that the tour packages pouring out of San Jose regrettably fail to recount. The truth is, while eco-tourism and liberal trade agreements have brought prosperity to some in Costa Rica, many Ticos still live below the poverty line. Is ignorance bliss? We Kiva Lenders know better. INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
