(298, 1, '2010-10-18 20:39:24', '2010-10-18 20:39:24', '<div>\r\n<div>In August 2009, BRUTE LABS excitedly <a href="http://blog.brutelabs.org/2009_08_01_archive.html">announced</a> that we’d received a grant of over $10,000 to bring RUN! to thousands of low-income students throughout the Bay Area. Our team immediately set out to recruit schools, design program materials and assemble and distribute project kits. While we knew that executing on this program wouldn’t be as simple as duplicating our 2007 <a href="http://www.brutelabs.org/run.html">success</a> fifteen times over, we were certain that we could get the job done in a typical BRUTE fashion.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>However, our initial momentum was quickly tempered. The go-it-alone approach, that we so often employ, proved to be an obstacle in our efforts to scale RUN!. The sheer number of tasks associated with this project and the amount of community support required to get the program implemented quickly challenged our approach and forced us to evaluate and acknowledge the importance of partnering with others.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>Project management and effective communication proved to be of the utmost importance. Executing on our core competencies of design concepts, execution and technological implementation was easy. Keeping our partners and supporters on the same page and timeline wasn’t. Learning to tackle the unique challenges associated with this project and working to leverage and integrate the efforts of our partners provided another opportunity for our organization to continue to grow. Continuous change calls for continuous improvement. With RUN!, we got a chance to see what BRUTE LABS is truly capable of accomplishing.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>On March 30, we announced the <a href="http://blog.brutelabs.org/2010_03_01_archive.html">launch of RUN!</a> at fifteen Bay Area <a href="http://www.brutelabs.org/run/">schools</a>. Throughout the duration of the program, we remained agile and open-minded as we received reports of the notable challenges faced by teachers and the undeniable success stories that the program generated. In a little over two months, we saw students completing an incredible number of laps and setting personal bests in their mile times. The average students ran 25 laps and 4 miles. At the start of the program, the kids ran at an average time of 15 minutes per mile. By the end of the program, the kids ran at an average of 9 minutes per mile. The feedback from the community is overwhelming and we’re receiving many requests to continue the program.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>As we move the RUN! project into its next chapter, we’re taking a close look at what we did. Highlighting what went right and, examining even more closely, our areas for improvement. As is our organization’s vision, we are staunch supporters of open source altruism. Given this goal, we’re working to ensure that RUN! can be scaled for use by any educator or community members looking to get young people out of their seats and into their running shoes!</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>Most importantly, let us close by extending a huge thanks to all the teachers, administrators, graphic designers, printers, paper companies, volunteers, parents and - most importantly - students that believed in RUN! and helped to make the program a success!</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n&nbsp;', 'Measuring the Impact of RUN!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'measuring-the-impact-of-run', '', '', '2012-10-31 20:43:28', '2012-10-31 20:43:28', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/?p=298', 0, 'post', '', 0),
