(303, 1, '2012-10-31 20:41:18', '2012-10-31 20:41:18', '<div>\r\n<div>In August 2009, BRUTE LABS excitedly <a href="http://blog.brutelabs.org/2009_08_01_archive.html">announced</a> that we’d received a grant of over $10,000 to bring RUN! to thousands of low-income students throughout the Bay Area. Our team immediately set out to recruit schools, design program materials and assemble and distribute project kits. While we knew that executing on this program wouldn’t be as simple as duplicating our 2007 <a href="http://www.brutelabs.org/run.html">success</a> fifteen times over, we were certain that we could get the job done in a typical BRUTE fashion.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>However, our initial momentum was quickly tempered. The go-it-alone approach, that we so often employ, proved to be an obstacle in our efforts to scale RUN!. The sheer number of tasks associated with this project and the amount of community support required to get the program implemented quickly challenged our approach and forced us to evaluate and acknowledge the importance of partnering with others.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>Project management and effective communication proved to be of the utmost importance. Executing on our core competencies of design concepts, execution and technological implementation was easy. Keeping our partners and supporters on the same page and timeline wasn’t. Learning to tackle the unique challenges associated with this project and working to leverage and integrate the efforts of our partners provided another opportunity for our organization to continue to grow. Continuous change calls for continuous improvement. With RUN!, we got a chance to see what BRUTE LABS is truly capable of accomplishing.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>On March 30, we announced the <a href="http://blog.brutelabs.org/2010_03_01_archive.html">launch of RUN!</a> at fifteen Bay Area <a href="http://www.brutelabs.org/run/">schools</a>. Throughout the duration of 